The noble metal Pd has a high work function of 5.6 eV (vs. E
                        vac.
                     ) and its Fermi energy level is lower than the conduction band (CB) potential of the TiO2. This potential difference, as a driving force, would greatly accelerate the photogenerated electron transfer from the CB of TiO2 to the Pd, and consequently improve the separation of electrons and holes [35–37]. Loading Pd nanoparticles on a TiO2 may also enhance its light absorption capacity in visible region due to surface plasma resonance effect of the Pd nanoparticles. Thus, Pd nanoparticles have been recognized as an excellent candidate co-catalyst of the TiO2 nanomaterials. For instance, Wu et al. prepared a series of Pd/TiO2 photocatalysts with different surface structures by various methods and found that the partial oxidation of toluene were highly determined by the valence states of Pd particles [38]. The relatively higher concentration of Pd0 species on the Pd/TiO2–N could facilitate enhancement of the photocatalytic activity. Wahab reported the dual metal decorated Ag–Pd/TiO2 catalyst for photocatalytic reforming and oxidation of glycerol [39]. However, to the best of our knowledge, there has been no report on the ternary composite Pd-CQDs/TiO2 for photocatalytic H2 production. Moreover, fulfilling complete conversion of Pd2+ to Pd0 on the surface of TiO2 to increase activity of the catalyst is still a challenging task. Besides, the photocatalytic reaction mechanism, especially the synergistic effect of Pd nanoparticles and CQDs on the enhanced photocatalytic H2 production activity of the TiO2 nanosheets was lack of study.

In order to explore the photocatalytic reaction mechanism over the Pd-0.5CQDs/TiO2, the work functions, CB potentials and VB potentials of the materials are required to learn the migrations of the electrons and holes. The Mott-Schottky (M − S) plots of the pure TiO2 NSs, CQDs and the ternary composite Pd-0.5CQDs/TiO2 have been measured to obtain the CB potentials of the materials, as seen in Fig. 9
                        . The detailed description on the calculations of CB potentials of the TiO2 NSs, CQDs and Pd-0.5CQDs/TiO2 can be found in the ESI. The CB potentials of the pure TiO2 NSs, pure CQDs and Pd-0.5CQDs/TiO2 are −0.32, −0.14 eV and −0.21 eV, respectively. The work functions and VB potentials of the pure TiO2 and CQDs were obtained from the UPS spectra and VB XPS spectra (Fig. 10
                        ). The work functions of the pure TiO2 NSs and the pure CQDs were calculated by referring to the method in literature [55], which are 4.18 and 4.99 eV, respectively, and the VB potentials are 2.74 and 2.37 eV (vs. NHE), respectively. According to the measured values of the CB and VB potentials of the pure TiO2, its band gap energy was calculated as 3.06 eV, which is similar to the value obtained from the DRS spectra.
